        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Configuration-as-Code for LLM Systems"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Configuration-as-code (CaC) is the discipline of storing every value that controls system behaviour in version-controlled files rather than in dashboards, flag stores, or the minds of engineers. For an LLM system the configuration surface is wide: model identifiers, prompt templates, eval thresholds, canary stage parameters, and Kubernetes resource limits all affect production quality. Putting them all in Git means that every change is reviewed, tested, rolled back by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "git revert",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and auditable via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "git log",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Goes in Version Control"
          }
        ]
